Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 91st Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Been a busy week here at Not Boring HQ: Packy ran a 2:58 in his first ever =
marathon on Sunday, then dropped a 15K word essay on the future of mining [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/1bad5a10-0f7e-4534-83e7-8fd9562e9ff8?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on Tuesday, a=
nd I have been dealing with insatiable demand for Create=E2=80=99s new Sour=
 Green Apple creatine gummies [ https://substack.com/redirect/5735641d-3d5a=
-425c-b9cd-bc3041b27418?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (code: notboring30 for 30% off). But amid all of that bus=
yness, the world kept marching onwards and upwards. Solid national policy d=
ecisions, AI powering more of modern medicine and defense, and much more. W=
e=E2=80=99re here to cover it.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) Anduril Selected for U.S. Air Force Collaborative Combat Aircraft Progr=
am [ https://substack.com/redirect/8b540cd0-3a8c-4c68-9c87-5116e546f690?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Anduril
Today, the United States Air Force announced that Anduril has been selected=
 as one of two vendors to move forward on the Collaborative Combat Aircraft=
 (CCA) program. Over the next phase, Anduril will design, manufacture, and =
test production-representative CCAs.
In a very serious nod of recognition, The U.S. Air Force has selected Andur=
il as one of two vendors to design, manufacture, and test production-repres=
entative Collaborative Combat Aircraft (CCA). You might think, what=E2=80=
=99s the big deal=E2=80=A6isn=E2=80=99t this exactly what Anduril was desig=
ned to do? You=E2=80=99re right and that=E2=80=99s true =E2=80=94 Anduril i=
s competing in exactly the ways it was designed to, but is doing so just 7 =
years after launching. It beat out Boeing, Lockheed Martin and Northrop Gru=
mman for the deal. As Anduril=E2=80=99s founder, Palmer Luckey, posted, =E2=
=80=9CAnduril is proving that with the right team and business model, a sev=
en-year-old company can go toe-to-toe with players that have been around fo=
r 70+. The real winner? The United States of America.=E2=80=9D
Anduril=E2=80=99s success is evidence that new companies and approaches can=
 take on even the most regulatorily captured of industries. That disruption=
 is not only going to force existing primes to up their game, but also enco=
urage other startups to enter the market. To them, what was previously impo=
ssible now seems feasible. There=E2=80=99s a playbook for it.
But what=E2=80=99s a CCA anyway? It=E2=80=99s an unmanned aircraft designed=
 to work alongside crewed planes, enhancing capabilities through teaming. I=
t utilizes automation and AI to do reconnaissance, targeting, and supportin=
g manned aircraft in complex operations. Anduril=E2=80=99s current CCA offe=
ring is called Fury, although it is still unclear what changes will be made=
 to the existing craft as part of the Air Force=E2=80=99s procurement proce=
ss. Ultimately, the USAF will make a final, multibillion-dollar production =
decision in two years from now =E2=80=94 it said that it wants ~1,000 craft=
 =E2=80=94 with the goal of having fully operational crafts by the end of t=
he decade.
We=E2=80=99re big believers that Techno-Industrialists will create much big=
ger businesses than people expect by taking on large old industries with be=
tter products and margins. We used Anduril as example A1 in The Techno-Indu=
strial Revolution [ https://substack.com/redirect/00575ef9-d571-4f60-8dfa-6=
e173575dd73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]. This win is a big step in that direction, showing that startups don=
=E2=80=99t need to nibble around the edges but can attack the incumbents he=
ad-on. Nothing more optimistic than that.=20
To learn more about Anduril=E2=80=99s strategy, check out our deep dive:=20
For more Anduril fun, Madeline Renbarger at Newcomer has a great profile on=
 Anduril co-founder and Founders Fund partner Trae Stephens (paywalled =F0=
=9F=94=92).
(2) President Biden signs law to ban TikTok nationwide unless it is sold [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/3093f5c8-413e-4ca6-83bd-67064e0b2a44?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From NPR
President Biden on Wednesday signed a law that would ban Chinese-owned TikT=
ok unless it is sold within a year. It is the most serious threat yet to th=
e video-streaming app's future in the U.S., intensifying America's tech war=
 with China.
You know what else Palmer Luckey was right about before everyone else? Bann=
ing TikTok. His rationale was simple: they ban our apps, it makes no econom=
ic sense not to fight back.=20
We=E2=80=99re not China hawks here and generally are skeptical of governmen=
ts banning apps, but this one just seemed too obvious not to root for. Base=
d on the evidence available, TikTok in its current form is both an agent of=
 the CCP and one of the most popular sources of information in the United S=
tates. Those two realities just could not coexist much longer. We=E2=80=99r=
e not the first to make this analogy, but it would be like allowing the USS=
R to own CBS during the Cold War. There are plenty of other platforms for f=
ree speech whose algorithms aren=E2=80=99t controlled by a foreign adversar=
y, and in new hands, TikTok could be one of them! To me, this is less an es=
calation of U.S. <> China relations and more just good national policy hygi=
ene.=20
So why is this an optimistic story? It=E2=80=99s a solid signal that bipart=
isanship and common sense policy can still prevail, even in the face of spe=
cial interests and even during a hyper-polarized period in American politic=
s. Congress can still come together and do what needs to be done for the be=
tterment of the nation. Sure, it was tucked into a much larger $95B foreign=
 aid package, but ultimately The House, Senate, and Biden Administration ca=
me together to make it happen.
Who knows how this all plays out =E2=80=94 ByteDance will certainly fight t=
his in court (as they should and is their right!) and if they lose you=E2=
=80=99d imagine they=E2=80=99ll be some pretty interested U.S. buyers. But =
a world in which TikTok is not owned by ByteDance (and therefore controlled=
 by the CCP), is likely a slightly safer and more stable world.=20
(3) Astribot S1 Hello World [ https://substack.com/redirect/cc54885c-133c-4=
c35-a157-949cf9c31148?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
h/t to Martin Prince-Parrott for surfacing [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
c5f57a38-da64-4828-bd59-08629e12f4f6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Now for some very cool news out of China!=20
Y=E2=80=99all have to let us sleep. We had the Weekly Dose all wrapped up a=
nd ready to go when, overnight, the Chinese robotics company Stardust Intel=
ligence (Astribot) dropped maybe the most impressive robot video we=E2=80=
=99ve seen yet.=20
Its humanoid-ish robot opens beer and wine, flips bread in a pan, sorts a b=
unch of things on a table, peels a cucumber, folds a shirt, makes a step st=
ool, waters a plant, vacuums, throws something into a wastebasket, and even=
 dances and paints.=20
For the same reasons TikTok was banned, we probably won=E2=80=99t see Astri=
bots in every American home, but the video showed a glimpse into the very n=
ear future where general purpose robots do more of the housework while huma=
ns do human stuff. With so much capital and competition in robotics, it=E2=
=80=99s a matter of when (and how much?), not if.=20
(4) Profluent Successfully Edits Human Genome with OpenCRISPR-1, the World=
=E2=80=99s First AI-Created and Open-Source Gene Editor [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/4e994421-90e5-42aa-a252-3c1a37af3642?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Profluent, the AI-first protein design company, today debuted the OpenCRISP=
RTM initiative, releasing the world=E2=80=99s first open-source, AI-generat=
ed gene editor. With this launch, Profluent demonstrates the first successf=
ul precision editing of the human genome with customizable gene editors des=
igned from scratch with AI.
Profluent released OpenCRISPR-1, the first AI-designed gene editor. And not=
 only that, the company announced it would be open sourcing the molecules s=
o others can build on top of their work.
OpenCRISPR-1 is a Cas9-like protein and guide RNA gene editor entirely deve=
loped using the company=E2=80=99s proprietary LLMs, which were trained to p=
roduce novel CRISPR-like proteins that expand the known CRISPR families. Op=
enCRISPR didn't just replicate existing CRISPR systems; it generated new, d=
iverse CRISPR-like proteins. Ultimately, the new toolkit could allow for mo=
re sophisticated, precise, and accessible gene editing methodologies.
I say this every week, but with new companies like Profluent constantly pop=
ping up, I just think it=E2=80=99s a really bad time to be a disease in thi=
s world.
(5) Crypto is back. Stripe will start supporting global stablecoin payments=
=2E [ https://substack.com/redirect/3b=
2953d0-c919-4fcf-b933-c20920c483fc?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. Yesterday at Stripe Sessions, co-founder John Collison gave a p=
resentation called The Future of Payments. The future? Crypto. More specifi=
cally: stablecoins.=20
In a live demo, John checks out, chooses to pay in crypto with Stripe [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/c4bd0386-302b-44c7-8942-284e7246f56d?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and shows off th=
e surprisingly low fees and fast speed of paying in USDC [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/ad7ac1e1-03f5-424d-b04=
e-94acf2100b8e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on Solana [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/0c87c319-396a-42de-8bc5-9c5a7cbedb4c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] via the Phantom wallet. It settl=
ed in less than a second instead of the days it would take via credit card =
and cost $0.0037 in network fees on a $99 transaction, 800x less than the 3=
% you=E2=80=99d pay if you were using a credit card.
What happens to the GDP of the internet when everything gets 3% cheaper?=20
It=E2=80=99s a win for consumers (who pay lower fees), for merchants (who g=
et paid instantly), and for Stripe (which expands its margins, circumvents =
the credit card companies, and potentially lays more groundwork to compete =
with the credit card networks).=20
This is a great example of crypto simply making capitalism more effective [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/7551e55d-e18a-4ca9-8133-0f6535edb2a0?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and winning =
by providing a much better solution. How=E2=80=99s that for a use case?
Bonus: Stripe Sculpture [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca8e533f-40f1-4149-=
847f-9474105760a7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]
From the future to the past.=20
The team at Monumental Labs, which builds AI-enabled robotic stone carving =
factories, unveiled its Stripe sculpture at Stripe Sessions. We actually co=
vered this team in our January essay on the companies leading the Techno-In=
dustrial Revolution [ https://substack.com/redirect/00575ef9-d571-4f60-8dfa=
-6e173575dd73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]. Supposedly the team went from initial design to robot sculpting to=
 hand finishing the sculpture in just one month.=20
Imagine how much beauty Monumental will bring into the world in the years a=
head.
I just wish they had asked before using Packy=E2=80=99s NIL.
Double Bonus!: Affordable, rapid bootstrapping of space industry and solar =
system civilization [ https://substack.com/redirect/b560cb76-035a-417b-bfdf=
-7ce66efff2b4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
NASA via David Holz
It has become feasible to bootstrap a self-sustaining, self-expanding indus=
try at reasonably low cost. Simple modeling was developed to identify the m=
ain parameters of successful bootstrapping. This indicates that bootstrappi=
ng can be achieved with as little as 12 metric tons (MT) landed on the Moon=
 during a period of about 20 years.
In 2016, NASA wrote a paper describing what it would take to bootstrap self=
-replicating robot space economies within a century. We don=E2=80=99t norma=
lly cover eight-year-old papers here, but David Holz surfaced this one yest=
erday and it=E2=80=99s an awesome read.=20
The paper shows that due to advances in robotics and additive manufacturing=
 (3D printing), it would be possible to send 12 metric tons of material to =
the moon and build robotic systems that build bigger robotic systems that h=
arvest the resources of the moon and then the solar system to ultimately pr=
ovide orders of magnitude more industrial output in space than we can achie=
ve on earth.=20
First, it=E2=80=99s just awesome that there are rocket scientists at NASA c=
runching the numbers on self-replicating robotic space industries. Second, =
with the advances in launch capabilities, robotics, and 3D printing since t=
he paper was written, it looks like the authors were on to something. As Ho=
lz points out, they may have been conservative: they didn=E2=80=99t factor =
in lower launch costs with Starship, the ability to grow anything with synt=
hetic biology, or the intelligence with which entrepreneurs are beginning t=
o infuse robots.=20
This will happen. We have companies like General Fabrication [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/bcaa7ebe-26b4-4a5e-bbe6-62823d8b6189?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] working on it here on eart=
h, and no physical reason we won=E2=80=99t be able to tap into the vast res=
ources of space.=20
The near future will be abundant if we let it. To that end, we were pumped =
to see the launch of the Abundance Institute [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/d95c617a-e615-4a32-8ffd-28db89b0818d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] by some Not Boring favorites like Eli Dour=
ado and J. Storrs Hall this week to make sure we let it.=20
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

